The other factor starving the industry of blockbuster beauty deals is the e=
maciation of the strategics themselves. Unilever lost Vasiliki Petrou, the =
brilliant C.E.O. of its prestige division, who spearheaded 10 acquisitions.=
 Est=C3=A9e Lauder is under financial pressure and undergoing a major execu=
tive shake-up following the exit of C.E.O. Fabrizio Freda. Shiseido=E2=80=
=99s market capitalization has fallen to an eight-year low. Then there=E2=
=80=99s Johnson & Johnson, which spun off its consumer health and products =
division last year. Kenvue, the newly created consumer healthco, literally =
had no leadership until last month.

There=E2=80=99s still 27 days left in 2024, so anything can happen. After a=
ll, it was on December 22 of last year that Unilever and Shiseido announced=
 they would be acquiring K18 and Dr. Dennis Gross, respectively. Regardless=
 of
whether the industry experiences a Christmas miracle, I=E2=80=99m still hol=
ding out for 2025. Generally, the market seems more optimistic since the el=
ection, and there=E2=80=99s hope that interest rates will continue to tumbl=
e. Still, sellers will need to get over their delusions of grand valuations=
 and meet potential buyers halfway.

That=E2=80=99s it from Rachel and me. By the way, it absolutely cracks me u=
p that the entire industry has, for the past three months, been obsessing o=
ver a guy buying an apartment in Milan. I, too, hope it means that Hedi Sli=
mane has a job in that city. But also=E2=80=A6 maybe he just likes visiting=
 Milan? It=E2=80=99s really nice these days! Also, can someone log on to th=
e Italian registrar and prove to me that he actually bought it and is not j=
ust renting from a friend?

Until tomorrow,
Lauren

