          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">So that big year we=
 were promised for beauty M&amp;A hasn=E2=80=99t <i>quite </i>shaken out as=
 planned. Yes, Charlotte Tilbury and Puig teamed up to buy a majority stake=
 in Dr. Barbara Sturm for about $240 million. And Helen of Troy, the public=
ly traded brand developer, paid $225 million (plus layered incentives) to a=
cquire <b>Sarah Gibson Tuttle</b>=E2=80=99s Olive &amp; June in a deal orch=
estrated by our girl <b>Vennette Ho</b>. And yes, there have also been some=
 small to moderate transactions and a handful of private equity deals, incl=
uding at Summer Fridays, Kiko Milano, and Winky Lux. But neither Rare nor G=
lossier nor even Makeup by Mario, all of which were exploring their exit op=
tions earlier this year, seem any closer to a liquidity event. <br/><br/>Me=
anwhile, Summer Fridays turned to private equity after the lopsided success=
 of one of its viral products spooked
strategic investors. Osea, a skincare label doing about $100 million in rev=
enue, <i>almost</i> closed a deal with Shiseido=E2=80=A6 but it fell throug=
h. Strategics, like Est=C3=A9e or L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al, have been particula=
rly quiet as they prioritize their own economic challenges. A top banker re=
cently described the industry=E2=80=99s M&amp;A scene in a word: =E2=80=9Cd=
epressing.=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
         </tr>
