          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The other factor st=
arving the industry of blockbuster beauty deals is the emaciation of the st=
rategics themselves. Unilever lost <b>Vasiliki Petrou</b>, the brilliant C.=
E.O. of its prestige division, who spearheaded 10 acquisitions. Est=C3=A9e =
Lauder is under financial pressure and undergoing a major executive shake-u=
p following the exit of C.E.O. <b>Fabrizio Freda</b>. Shiseido=E2=80=99s ma=
rket capitalization has fallen to an eight-year low. Then there=E2=80=99s J=
ohnson &amp; Johnson, which spun off its consumer health and products divis=
ion last year. Kenvue, the newly created consumer healthco, literally had n=
o leadership until last month.<br/><br/>There=E2=80=99s still 27 days left =
in 2024, so anything can happen. After all, it was on December 22 of last y=
ear that Unilever and Shiseido announced they would be acquiring K18 and Dr=
=2E Dennis Gross, respectively. Regardless of
whether the industry experiences a Christmas miracle, I=E2=80=99m still hol=
ding out for 2025. Generally, the market seems more optimistic since the el=
ection, and there=E2=80=99s hope that interest rates will continue to tumbl=
e. Still, sellers will need to get over their delusions of grand valuations=
 and meet potential buyers halfway. <br/></td>
